story cried out for vigorous cross-examination. In the end the too-deferential, easygoing Mitchell failed to provide much, if anything, in the way of evidence against Ford or in favor of Kavanaugh. Whether her work will bring over fence-sitting senators to Kavanaughâ€™s side remains to be seen. Like other Democrats, Sen. Mazie Hirono of Hawaii tried to help Ford, lobbing her softballs. After saying she thought she knew what Mitchell was trying to get at in her questions, the senator said, â€œso I'll just ask you very plainly, Dr. Ford, is there a political motivation for your coming forward with your account of the assault by Brett Kavanaugh?â€ â€œNo, and I'd like to reiterate that again, I was trying to get the information to you while there was still a list of other what looked like equally-qualified candidates,â€ Ford replied. When Sen. Dick Durbin (D-Ill.) asked Ford â€œwith what degree of certainty do you believe Brett Kavanaugh assaulted you?â€ Ford replied, â€œone hundred percent.â€ Strangely, Ford has a bad long-term memory and a bad short-term memory. She doesnâ€™t know when or where the alleged incident took place, yet she is â€œone hundred percentâ€ certain it was Kavanaugh who attacked her. At the outset of the hearing, Grassley provided an overview of what Kavanaugh had gone through â€“including the Democratsâ€™ sordid behaviorâ€” since President Trump announced the judgeâ€™s nomination on July 9. As part of the confirmation process, Kavanaugh endured his sixth background investigation since 1993. â€œNowhere in any of these six FBI reports, which committee investigators have reviewed on a bipartisan basis, was there a whiff of any issue â€“ any issue at all related in any way to inappropriate sexual behavior,â€ Grassley said. Ford shared her allegations in a letter to the committeeâ€™s ranking member, Dianne Feinstein (D-Calif.), in the summer. The letter remained secret from July 30 through until September 13 when he first learned about it, the chairma